oc:kn_01b522aa a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When calculating LTV, CAC, or LTV:CAC ratio" ;
    oc:directiveContent "LTV calculation requires ARPU × Gross Margin / Churn Rate. Do not use revenue-only LTV without gross margin adjustment. LTV:CAC ratio must exceed 3x for healthy unit economics; below 1x means the business is destroying value." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Ignoring gross margin in LTV overstates lifetime value and leads to over-investment in acquisition; the 3x threshold ensures CAC payback is reasonable." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_104da630 a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When reporting churn metrics" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never use logo churn alone as a proxy for revenue health — always compute both logo churn (customer count) and revenue churn (MRR-based) alongside Net Revenue Retention (NRR)." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Logo churn masks revenue dynamics if high-value and low-value customers churn at different rates; NRR captures expansion which logo churn ignores." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_190556c4 a oc:CodePattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When calculating unit economics" ;
    oc:codeLanguage "yaml" ;
    oc:directiveContent """LTV = (ARPU × Gross_Margin) / Churn_Rate
CAC = Sales_Marketing_Spend / New_Customers
LTV_CAC_Ratio = LTV / CAC
CAC_Payback = CAC / (ARPU × Gross_Margin)""" .

oc:kn_3d6c394e a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Procedure ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When performing comprehensive SaaS metrics analysis" ;
    oc:directiveContent "1. Gather subscription data (active, new, upgraded, downgraded, cancelled). 2. Calculate MRR components and waterfall. 3. Compute churn metrics (logo, gross revenue, net revenue, NRR). 4. Calculate unit economics (LTV, CAC, LTV:CAC, CAC payback). 5. Build cohort retention matrix. 6. Segment by plan/industry/company size. 7. Generate investor report with benchmarks and status indicators." ;
    oc:stepOrder 1 .

oc:kn_5d89eb7c a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Prerequisite ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Before running any SaaS metrics analysis" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Subscription data source required — either spreadsheet with active subscriptions, billing system (Stripe/Chargebee), or manual MRR/ARR inputs" .

oc:kn_5e611423 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:KnownIssue ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When building 12-month revenue projections" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Bottom-up revenue forecasts compound assumptions monthly — small errors in churn rate or expansion rate assumptions amplify over 12 months. Always stress-test forecasts with sensitivity analysis on key assumptions." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Compounding means a 1% churn assumption error can shift year-end ARR projections by 15-20%, leading to misinformed planning." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_727f59f7 a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When generating investor reports or dashboards" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Segment all metrics by plan tier, industry, and company size. Present investor reports with current vs. previous period comparison, benchmarks, and emoji status indicators (✅ ⚠️ 🔴)." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Segmentation reveals where churn is concentrated and where expansion revenue originates; benchmarking provides context for metrics that are meaningless in isolation." .

oc:kn_8a963e11 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When assessing overall SaaS growth efficiency" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Quick Ratio = (new MRR + expansion MRR) / (contraction MRR + churn MRR). Use it as a single-number health check: <1 = shrinking, 1-2 = sustainable, 2-4 = good growth, >4 = hypergrowth potential." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Quick Ratio condenses growth and churn into one metric, making it ideal for rapid health checks and trend monitoring." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_9935bf7e a oc:CodePattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When calculating revenue metrics" ;
    oc:codeLanguage "yaml" ;
    oc:directiveContent """MRR: sum(all_active_subscriptions.monthly_value)
ARR: MRR × 12
net_new_mrr: new_mrr + expansion_mrr + reactivation_mrr - contraction_mrr - churn_mrr
mrr_growth_rate: (ending_mrr - starting_mrr) / starting_mrr × 100""" .

oc:kn_9dd30f1d a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:OutputFormat ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When generating investor monthly metrics report" ;
    oc:directiveContent """# {Company} - Monthly Metrics Report
## {Month Year}
### Key Metrics Summary
| Metric | Current | Previous | Change | Benchmark |
### MRR Waterfall
### Customer Metrics (by segment)
### Runway & Burn
### Goals vs Actuals
### Next Month Outlook""" ;
    oc:templateVariables "Company",
        "Month Year" .

oc:kn_d40ff941 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:OutputFormat ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When generating churn analysis report" ;
    oc:directiveContent """## Churn Analysis - {Month}
### Summary (Logo Churn, Gross Revenue Churn, NRR with benchmarks)
### Churn Breakdown (by reason: Price, Competitor, No longer needed, Product issues, Other)
### Cohort Performance""" ;
    oc:templateVariables "Month" .

oc:kn_e358a9f0 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Standard ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When calculating any MRR/ARR metrics" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Always decompose MRR changes into five components: new MRR, expansion MRR, reactivation MRR, contraction MRR, and churn MRR. Net New MRR = new + expansion + reactivation - contraction - churn." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Decomposing MRR into components reveals the true growth drivers vs. just the net result, enabling targeted interventions." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

